        <p>
          Graphically, you would plot the frequency column against the Bin or the Range column. The following Python Code will produce the plot given below.
        </p>
        
        <program language="python" line-numbers="yes">
            import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
            import numpy as np

            # Data
            data = [0, 2, 2, 3, 3, 6, 7, 7, 8, 10]

            # Desired bin size
            bin_size = 2

            # Calculate bin edges
            min_val = min(data)
            max_val = max(data)
            bins = np.arange(min_val, max_val + bin_size, bin_size)

            # Plotting the histogram
            plt.hist(data, bins=bins, edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7)

            # Adding labels and title
            plt.xlabel('Value')
            plt.ylabel('Frequency')
            plt.title(f'Histogram of Data with Bin Size = {bin_size}')

            # Display the plot
            plt.xticks(bins) # Optional: to show bin edges as x-axis ticks
            plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.75) # Optional: add a grid for better readability
            plt.show()

        </program>
        <figure xml:id="fig-descriptive-statistics-histogram">
          <caption>Histogram with data in range 1 to 10 with bin size 2.</caption>
